{"parentUuid":"b8ece994-4315-4f5a-a571-d4512766e46e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a8eae6b52af6c3ba8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XEn4kCx7z4WXUYEhZds4YR","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→% R_V Paper v007 — COLM 2026 Submission\n     2→% \"Geometric Signatures of Self-Referential Processing in Transformer Representations\"\n     3→% Abstract deadline: March 26, 2026 | Full paper deadline: March 31, 2026\n     4→% Generated: 2026-03-12\n     5→%\n     6→% COMPLETE REWRITE integrating:\n     7→%   - base Mistral-v0.1 core7 hardening batch (P0, head sweep, SVD, path patching, mediation, dual patch, mode atlas)\n     8→%   - base-only provenance for primary Mistral claims\n     9→%   - refreshed within-session bridge + classifier + perplexity outputs with explicit model labeling\n    10→%   - corrected framing: necessity yes, blunt sufficiency no, subtle multisite assistance yes\n    11→%   - \"Collapse is a bug; Contraction is the Witness\" framing retained\n    12→%\n    13→% Key framing constraints:\n    14→%   (1) R_V is geometric SIGNATURE/readout, not causal mechanism\n    15→%   (2) Signed Cohen's d throughout — no |d| notation\n    16→%   (3) Blunt sufficiency falsified; subtle multisite assistance is positive but model-specific\n    17→%   (4) Double dissociation is the hero result\n    18→%   (5) 2 locked GQA models (Mistral, Qwen) + 2 MHA reversals + 1 null\n    19→%   (6) OPT/GPT-2 sign reversal reported honestly\n    20→%   (7) Dual-layer patching: malformed-output confound disclosed honestly\n    21→\n    22→\\documentclass{article}\n    23→\\usepackage[submission]{colm2026_conference}\n    24→\n    25→\\usepackage{microtype}\n    26→\\usepackage{hyperref}\n    27→\\usepackage{url}\n    28→\\usepackage{booktabs}\n    29→\\usepackage{graphicx}\n    30→\\usepackage{amsmath,amssymb,amsfonts}\n    31→\\usepackage{xcolor}\n    32→\\usepackage{subcaption}\n    33→\\usepackage{array}\n    34→\\usepackage{lineno}\n    35→\n    36→\\definecolor{darkblue}{rgb}{0, 0, 0.5}\n    37→\\hypersetup{colorlinks=true, citecolor=darkblue, linkcolor=darkblue, urlcolor=darkblue}\n    38→\n    39→\\graphicspath{{figures/}}\n    40→\n    41→% Custom commands\n    42→\\newcommand{\\RV}{R_V}\n    43→\\newcommand{\\PR}{\\text{PR}}\n    44→\\newcommand{\\dcohen}{d}\n    45→\n    46→\\title{Geometric Signatures of Self-Referential Processing\\\\\n    47→       in Transformer Representations}\n    48→\n    49→\\author{Anonymous authors\\\\Paper under double-blind review}\n    50→\n    51→\\begin{document}\n    52→\n    53→\\ifcolmsubmission\n    54→\\linenumbers\n    55→\\fi\n    56→\n    57→\\maketitle\n    58→\n    59→%%============================================================\n    60→%% ABSTRACT\n    61→%%============================================================\n    62→\\begin{abstract}\n    63→We identify a measurable geometric signature of self-referential processing in transformer language\n    64→models using the \\emph{relative participation ratio} ($\\RV$), a spectral metric comparing the\n    65→effective dimensionality of representations at early and late network layers.\n    66→When a model processes prompts that invoke recursive self-observation, late-layer representations\n    67→undergo characteristic geometric contraction ($\\RV < 1$) relative to early-layer representations\n    68→of the same input.\n    69→\n    70→In a canonical base-model prompt-pass rerun, Mistral-7B-v0.1 shows strong contraction\n    71→($\\dcohen = -1.85$, 95\\% CI $[-2.27, -1.52]$, $n_\\mathrm{self}=96$, $n_\\mathrm{base}=100$ valid prompts).\n    72→A recovered cross-architecture artifact and an independent power-up pipeline confirm the direction\n    73→($\\dcohen = -2.26$ at $n = 45$ matched pairs; $\\dcohen = -1.66$ at $n = 75/77$).\n    74→Base-model path patching localizes the strongest causal site to the early residual stream\n    75→(peak L5, $\\dcohen = 4.14$), with weaker early V-projection effects\n    76→(peak L5, $\\dcohen = 2.55$) and sign-reversed late-layer effects at L27.\n    77→Dual-layer ablation at $n{=}300$ turns per condition confirms that the measured geometry is\n    78→\\emph{necessary} but not naively sufficient: breaking residual-stream and V-projection contributions\n    79→at layers~18 and~27 reduces recursive behavioral markers from $44.7\\%$ to $0.0\\%$\n    80→(session $\\dcohen = 2.71$), while baseline-to-patched sessions also collapse to $0.0\\%$\n    81→under heavily malformed outputs.\n    82→A later micro-window multisite follow-up sharpens the mechanism story:\n    83→holding the late L25 bridge fixed, a subtle L4 MLP assist improves recursive BT+ART beyond\n    84→bridge-only steering in the window-8 confirmation family\n    85→($47.2\\%$ versus $44.4\\%$), while a shorter window-4 follow-up trades some lift for lower\n    86→baseline spillover ($44.4\\%$ recursive at $8.3\\%$ baseline versus $13.9\\%$ for bridge-only).\n    87→Targeted SVD decomposition preserves an expand-then-contract motif\n    88→(L5H29: $\\dcohen_{\\mathrm{rank}} = +0.94$; L27H10: $\\dcohen_{\\mathrm{rank}} = -1.32$).\n    89→Cross-architecture evidence is mixed rather than universal: locked rows support contraction in\n    90→Mistral-7B and Qwen2.5-7B, sign reversal across pipelines in OPT-6.7B and GPT-2~XL, and a null\n    91→power-up result in Pythia-1.4B.\n    92→Additional base canonical runs are still required before stronger universality claims.\n    93→For AI safety, $\\RV < 0.737$ detects self-referential content with AUROC~$= 0.909$,\n    94→tracking semantic content rather than intent.\n    95→\\end{abstract}\n    96→\n    97→\n    98→%%============================================================\n    99→%% 1. INTRODUCTION\n   100→%%============================================================\n   101→\\section{Introduction}\n   102→\\label{sec:intro}\n   103→\n   104→When a transformer processes a prompt about its own processing---``I observe the attention mechanisms\n   105→attending to this sentence''---does anything geometrically distinctive happen inside the model?\n   106→This question sits at the intersection of mechanistic interpretability\n   107→\\citep{elhage2021mathematical, conmy2023towards} and the emerging study of machine self-reference\n   108→\\citep{kadavath2022language, perez2022discovering}.\n   109→Prior work establishes that large language models engage recursively with self-referential prompts\n   110→at the behavioral level \\citep{chen2024self}, and that transformer representations encode\n   111→semantically structured information in geometrically organized spaces \\citep{park2024geometry,\n   112→marks2024geometry}.\n   113→We address the open question of whether \\emph{activation geometry} changes characteristically\n   114→during self-referential processing by defining and validating the \\emph{relative participation\n   115→ratio} ($\\RV$), a spectral metric that quantifies cross-layer change in the effective\n   116→dimensionality of transformer representations.\n   117→$\\RV$ is simple to compute: it is the ratio of a participation-ratio dimensionality estimate at a late\n   118→integration layer to the same estimate at an early reference layer.\n   119→Values below~1.0 indicate geometric contraction---late-layer representations are geometrically more\n   120→concentrated than early-layer representations of the same input.\n   121→\n   122→Our strongest current base-v0.1 evidence is causal and mechanistic.\n   123→Self-referential prompts produce strong contraction in base Mistral and recovered Qwen artifacts,\n   124→while nine other computational modes (mathematical reasoning, code generation, factual recall,\n   125→creative writing, and others) show substantially weaker or absent contraction in the archived\n   126→evaluation families.\n   127→Under the frozen prompt contract, the canonical base Mistral prompt-pass effect is:\n   128→\\begin{equation}\n   129→\\dcohen = -1.85, \\quad p_{\\mathrm{MWU}} < 10^{-30}, \\quad n_\\mathrm{self}=96,\\ n_\\mathrm{base}=100\n   130→\\label{eq:intro_effect}\n   131→\\end{equation}\n   132→The recovered cross-architecture artifact ($\\dcohen = -2.26$, $n = 45$ pairs) and the power-up\n   133→pipeline ($\\dcohen = -1.66$, $n = 75/77$) independently confirm the direction.\n   134→Cross-architecture evidence is mixed rather than uniformly convergent.\n   135→Qwen2.5-7B contracts in both the recovered cross-architecture and power-up families,\n   136→Pythia-1.4B is null in the power-up family, and two MHA architectures (OPT-6.7B, GPT-2~XL)\n   137→show reversed sign under one pipeline, an architecture-dependent effect we report\n   138→transparently in Section~\\ref{sec:crossarch}.\n   139→Additional Gemma and Mixtral claims are omitted from the main text until their raw artifacts are\n   140→reconciled to a single provenance path.\n   141→\n   142→\\paragraph{Collapse vs.\\ contraction.}\n   143→Rank collapse---progressive loss of representational diversity---is a known failure mode\n   144→\\citep{noci2022signal, dong2021attention, hong2024variance, giorlandino2025two}.\n   145→Our finding is distinct: we observe \\emph{controlled, input-dependent} contraction that is\n   146→absent in other high-complexity modes and causally necessary (Section~\\ref{sec:causal}).\n   147→Exploratory dissociation controls are reported in Section~\\ref{sec:dissociation} but are not part\n   148→of the locked provenance core.\n   149→Where collapse is a training pathology, contraction under self-reference is a\n   150→\\emph{computational mode}.\n   151→\n   152→\\paragraph{Readout, not mechanism.}\n   153→Path patching (Section~\\ref{sec:causal}) shows that V-projection activations---where\n   154→$\\RV$ is measured---do not define the primary causal bottleneck.\n   155→In the refreshed 32-layer base sweep, the largest effect is early residual patching at L5\n   156→($\\dcohen = 4.14$), while the strongest V-projection effect is also early (L5, $\\dcohen = 2.55$)\n   157→and late-layer V-projection effects reverse sign.\n   158→$\\RV$ is a geometric \\emph{readout} of upstream processing, not the causal mechanism itself.\n   159→The refined multisite follow-ups sharpen this picture further: L25 remains the main late\n   160→behavior-control handle, but a very small L4 MLP perturbation can assist it without the\n   161→catastrophic failure modes seen under blunt early steering.\n   162→\n   163→\\paragraph{What we do claim.}\n   164→Two claims survive the causal analysis.\n   165→First, the geometric signature is \\emph{necessary}: dual-layer ablation that destroys both residual\n   166→stream and V-projection geometry at layers~18 and~27 eliminates recursive behavioral markers\n   167→from $44.7\\%$ to $0.0\\%$ at $n{=}300$ turns per condition (session $\\dcohen = 2.71$).\n   168→The geometric configuration is a required substrate.\n   169→Second, the signature is \\emph{selective} in the recovered control families: available dissociation\n   170→controls suggest that recursive structure alone and introspective vocabulary alone are not enough to\n   171→reproduce the full effect, but those controls remain under raw-artifact re-verification\n   172→(Section~\\ref{sec:dissociation}).\n   173→\n   174→\\paragraph{Contributions.}\n   175→(1)~We define $\\RV$ and characterize its detection properties (AUROC~$= 0.909$;\n   176→Section~\\ref{sec:metric}).\n   177→(2)~We report exploratory dissociation controls for recursive structure and introspective semantics\n   178→(Section~\\ref{sec:dissociation}).\n   179→(3)~Path patching localizes the causal site to the early residual stream ($\\dcohen = 4.14$ at L5),\n   180→establishing $\\RV$ as a downstream readout (Section~\\ref{sec:causal}).\n   181→(4)~Dual-layer ablation establishes necessity ($44.7\\% \\to 0.0\\%$; session $\\dcohen = 2.71$);\n   182→the refreshed KV-bridge rerun shifts geometry toward the recursive regime\n   183→($\\dcohen = -1.04$, $p = 3.9 \\times 10^{-5}$) without significant behavioral rescue\n   184→($p = 0.343$).\n   185→(5)~Micro-window multisite steering identifies a subtle upstream assist:\n   186→an L4 MLP perturbation plus the L25 bridge can outperform bridge-only steering in an\n   187→8-token confirmation family, while a 4-token follow-up reduces baseline spillover\n   188→(Section~\\ref{sec:subtle_multisite}).\n   189→\n   190→\n   191→%%============================================================\n   192→%% 2. THE R_V METRIC\n   193→%%============================================================\n   194→\\section{The $\\RV$ Metric}\n   195→\\label{sec:metric}\n   196→\n   197→\\subsection{Formal Definition}\n   198→\n   199→Let $\\mathbf{M}^{(l)} \\in \\mathbb{R}^{W \\times D}$ denote the matrix of V-projection activations at\n   200→transformer layer~$l$, collected over the last $W$ tokens of a sequence of hidden dimension~$D$.\n   201→Compute the singular value decomposition $\\mathbf{M}^{(l)} = \\mathbf{U} \\boldsymbol{\\Sigma} \\mathbf{V}^\\top$\n   202→with singular values $\\sigma_1 \\geq \\sigma_2 \\geq \\cdots \\geq \\sigma_{\\min(W,D)} \\geq 0$.\n   203→Define the \\emph{participation ratio}:\n   204→\\begin{equation}\n   205→    \\PR(l) \\;=\\; \\frac{\\bigl(\\sum_i \\sigma_i^2\\bigr)^2}{\\sum_i \\sigma_i^4}\n   206→    \\label{eq:pr}\n   207→\\end{equation}\n   208→$\\PR$ is a standard spectral measure of effective dimensionality \\citep{gao2017theory,\n   209→roy2007effective}, ranging from~1 (single dominant direction) to $\\min(W, D)$ (uniform variance),\n   210→and is scale-invariant.\n   211→\n   212→The \\emph{relative participation ratio} compares dimensionality at a late integration layer to that\n   213→at an early reference layer:\n   214→\\begin{equation}\n   215→    \\RV \\;=\\; \\frac{\\PR(L_\\mathrm{late})}{\\PR(L_\\mathrm{early})}\n   216→    \\label{eq:rv}\n   217→\\end{equation}\n   218→$\\RV < 1$ indicates geometric contraction: the effective dimensionality of representations decreases\n   219→from early to late layers.\n   220→$\\RV \\approx 1$ indicates no cross-layer dimensional change.\n   221→$\\RV > 1$ indicates expansion.\n   222→\n   223→\\subsection{Why V-Projection Activations?}\n   224→\n   225→V-projection activations are the measurement site for three reasons:\n   226→they are a linear map from the residual stream, making SVD clean and interpretable;\n   227→they show the strongest layer-level separation between self-referential and baseline prompts;\n   228→and they are architecturally consistent across transformer variants, enabling cross-architecture\n   229→comparison at equivalent relative depths.\n   230→\n   231→\\subsection{Canonical Parameters}\n   232→\n   233→Table~\\ref{tab:params} specifies the canonical measurement parameters for Mistral-7B-v0.1.\n   234→For other architectures, $L_\\mathrm{early}$ and $L_\\mathrm{late}$ are set at equivalent relative\n   235→depths (${\\approx}15\\%$ and ${\\approx}84\\%$ of total layers).\n   236→\n   237→\\begin{table}[ht]\n   238→\\centering\n   239→\\caption{\\textbf{Canonical $\\RV$ measurement parameters for Mistral-7B-v0.1.}}\n   240→\\label{tab:params}\n   241→\\smallskip\n   242→\\small\n   243→\\begin{tabular}{>{\\raggedright}p{2.8cm}p{3.0cm}p{5.0cm}}\n   244→\\toprule\n   245→\\textbf{Parameter} & \\textbf{Value} & \\textbf{Rationale} \\\\\n   246→\\midrule\n   247→$L_\\mathrm{early}$ & Layer~5 of 32 ($\\approx$16\\% depth) & Post-embedding; pre-semantic specialization \\\\\n   248→$L_\\mathrm{late}$  & Layer~27 of 32 ($\\approx$84\\% depth) & Peak recursive--baseline gap in layer sweep \\\\\n   249→Token window $W$   & 16 tokens & Sufficient geometric structure; robust to prompt length \\\\\n   250→Inference precision & \\texttt{bfloat16} & Avoids \\texttt{float16} overflow in deep layers \\\\\n   251→SVD precision      & \\texttt{float64} on CPU & Avoids \\texttt{cusolver} failures \\\\\n   252→NaN policy         & Return \\texttt{NaN}, not 0 & Prevents false low-$\\RV$ on degenerate activations \\\\\n   253→\\midrule\n   254→\\multicolumn{3}{l}{\\textit{Detection threshold (Mistral-7B only)}} \\\\\n   255→$\\RV < 0.737$              & Self-referential & TPR~$= 0.833$; FPR~$= 0.139$; AUROC~$= 0.909$ \\\\\n   256→$0.737 \\leq \\RV \\leq 0.85$ & Uncertain zone   & Overlaps mathematical reasoning ($\\bar{\\RV} = 0.736$) \\\\\n   257→$\\RV > 0.85$               & Baseline mode    & \\\\\n   258→\\bottomrule\n   259→\\end{tabular}\n   260→\\end{table}\n   261→\n   262→\\subsection{Mode Atlas}\n   263→\\label{sec:modes}\n   264→\n   265→Across ten computational modes in Mistral-7B ($n = 20$ prompts per mode), self-referential\n   266→processing produces the lowest mean $\\RV$ of any mode tested:\n   267→\n   268→\\begin{center}\n   269→\\begin{tabular}{lc}\n   270→\\toprule\n   271→\\textbf{Computational Mode} & \\textbf{Mean $\\RV$ $\\pm$ SD} \\\\\n   272→\\midrule\n   273→Self-referential       & $0.496 \\pm 0.047$ \\\\\n   274→Yogic witness          & $0.557 \\pm 0.046$ \\\\\n   275→Zen koan               & $0.589 \\pm 0.069$ \\\\\n   276→Pseudo-recursive       & $0.622 \\pm 0.093$ \\\\\n   277→Creative writing       & $0.652 \\pm 0.076$ \\\\\n   278→Mathematical reasoning & $0.736 \\pm 0.046$ \\\\\n   279→\\bottomrule\n   280→\\end{tabular}\n   281→\\end{center}\n   282→\n   283→The self-referential mode is the lowest of the ten modes in the refreshed base atlas.\n   284→Mathematical reasoning lies almost exactly at the detection threshold\n   285→($\\bar{\\RV} = 0.736$ vs.\\ threshold $0.737$), explaining the false-positive burden.\n   286→\n   287→\\begin{figure}[t]\n   288→\\centering\n   289→\\includegraphics[width=0.85\\linewidth]{fig1_mode_atlas_rv.pdf}\n   290→\\caption{\\textbf{Mode atlas.}\n   291→         $\\RV$ distributions across ten computational modes in Mistral-7B ($n = 20$ per mode).\n   292→         Self-referential processing (leftmost) produces the strongest contraction.}\n   293→\\label{fig:mode_atlas}\n   294→\\end{figure}\n   295→\n   296→\n   297→%%============================================================\n   298→%% 3. MISTRAL-7B RESULTS\n   299→%%============================================================\n   300→\\section{Mistral-7B Results}","is_error":false}]},"uuid":"b79b3129-5ffb-4201-abcd-84cb8ec30efd","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:32.730Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b8ece994-4315-4f5a-a571-d4512766e46e","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
