{"parentUuid":"29b4e8d0-4eac-4cbf-96ce-04ac4a66fc29","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a8eae6b52af6c3ba8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VhH39uwKbBUj2c5bMrBNKi","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# MASTER AUDIT: R_V Paper vs Repo Data Verification\n     2→**Target:** COLM 2026 submission — `R_V_PAPER/paper_colm2026_v005.tex`\n     3→**Date:** 2026-03-09\n     4→**Purpose:** Every claim in the paper must be verified against actual data in this repo. Find contradictions, orphan findings, and gaps.\n     5→\n     6→---\n     7→\n     8→## INSTRUCTIONS FOR AGENTS\n     9→\n    10→You are auditing a mechanistic interpretability research repo. A paper has been written (694 lines of LaTeX) making specific quantitative claims. Your job is to verify EVERY claim against the actual data files in this repo.\n    11→\n    12→### Rules\n    13→1. **Do NOT read prior audit reports** in `agent_reviews/responses/` or `FEB_5_LATEST_AUDIT_*.md`. We need fresh eyes, not anchored opinions.\n    14→2. **Every verdict must cite an exact file path** with the actual value from that file.\n    15→3. **Do NOT trust the paper text.** Verify everything against raw data (JSON, CSV, Python output).\n    16→4. **If data is missing, say MISSING.** Do not infer or assume.\n    17→5. **You must read the paper first:** `R_V_PAPER/paper_colm2026_v005.tex`\n    18→6. **Time budget:** Focus on the 25 claims below. Do not explore tangentially.\n    19→\n    20→### Output Format\n    21→\n    22→Save your response to:\n    23→```\n    24→agent_reviews/responses/20260309__MODELNAME__COLM_PAPER_AUDIT.md\n    25→```\n    26→\n    27→Required header:\n    28→```\n    29→Title: COLM 2026 PAPER AUDIT\n    30→Date: 2026-03-09\n    31→Model: <your model name + version>\n    32→Audit duration: <approximate time spent>\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→---\n    36→\n    37→## PART A: CLAIM-BY-CLAIM VERIFICATION\n    38→\n    39→For each claim below, provide EXACTLY this format:\n    40→\n    41→```\n    42→### Claim [ID]: [short description]\n    43→- **Paper says:** [exact quote or paraphrase with line number]\n    44→- **Data file:** [exact path to the JSON/CSV that should contain this]\n    45→- **Data shows:** [actual values from that file]\n    46→- **Verdict:** CONFIRMED / CONTRADICTED / PARTIAL / NO_DATA\n    47→- **Severity:** CRITICAL / HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW\n    48→- **Notes:** [any context]\n    49→```\n    50→\n    51→### The 25 Claims to Verify\n    52→\n    53→**Cross-Architecture (Claims 1-7)**\n    54→\n    55→C1. Mistral-7B shows contraction with d=-1.66, CI [-2.08, -1.32], n=152\n    56→- Check: `results/power_up/mistral-7b_n80_result.json` and any n>80 files\n    57→- Check: Are n1=75 and n2=77 (as in Table 1) consistent with data?\n    58→\n    59→C2. Qwen2.5-7B shows contraction with d=-2.32, CI [-2.86, -1.90], n=124\n    60→- Check: `results/power_up/qwen2.5-7b_n100_result.json` and `qwen2.5-7b_n80_result.json`\n    61→\n    62→C3. OPT-6.7B: Paper uses |d|=1.68 in body text (line 197). What is the SIGNED d?\n    63→- Check: `results/power_up/opt-6.7b_n80_result.json`\n    64→- Check: Is recursive_mean > or < baseline_mean?\n    65→- CRITICAL: Does the data show contraction or EXPANSION?\n    66→\n    67→C4. GPT-2 XL: Paper uses |d|=1.52 in body text (line 198). What is the SIGNED d?\n    68→- Check: `results/power_up/gpt2-xl_n80_result.json`\n    69→- CRITICAL: Same question as C3.\n    70→\n    71→C5. Pythia-1.4B shows d=-0.006, p=0.88, n=124\n    72→- Check: `results/power_up/pythia-1.4b_n80_result.json`\n    73→\n    74→C6. Paper line 194 says \"contraction replicates in four models.\" Is this accurate given C3 and C4 findings?\n    75→\n    76→C7. Table 1 (lines 525-529) shows specific n1, n2 values. Do these match the JSON files?\n    77→\n    78→**Causal Claims (Claims 8-12)**\n    79→\n    80→C8. Necessity: d=3.29, n=300, \"breaks V-projections at L25 and L27\"\n    81→- Search: `results/` for any file containing these stats\n    82→- Check: What experiment script produced this? Does the script exist?\n    83→- Check: `results/path_patching/path_patching_summary_20260227_080128.json` — what does the V-proj path patching data actually show?\n    84→\n    85→C9. Sufficiency: d=-3.50, n=300, OR=13.96 for KV injection\n    86→- Search: `results/kv_sufficiency_matrix/` and `results/sufficiency_ladder/`\n    87→- CRITICAL: Does KV injection transfer R_V geometry (not just behavior)?\n    88→- Check: `docs/findings/R_V_BEHAVIORAL_DISSOCIATION.md` — what does it say about R_V transfer?\n    89→\n    90→C10. Paper line 231: \"reduces BT+ART from 56% to 27.7%\"\n    91→- Find the actual source data for these percentages\n    92→- Is 27.7% correct? Or is the actual number different?\n    93→\n    94→C11. Within-session bridge: d=-0.71, n=150\n    95→- Check: `results/within_session_bridge/`\n    96→\n    97→C12. V-projection path patching: For every layer tested, what is the V-proj Cohen's d?\n    98→- Check: `results/path_patching/path_patching_summary_20260227_080128.json`\n    99→- List the max V-proj |d| across all layers\n   100→- CRITICAL: Does this support or undermine the \"Value Spaces\" title?\n   101→\n   102→**Mode Atlas & Statistical (Claims 13-17)**\n   103→\n   104→C13. Self-referential R_V mean = 0.650, SD = 0.098, d=-1.67 vs all modes\n   105→- Check: `results/mode_atlas/`\n   106→\n   107→C14. 606/1024 heads significant at p<0.05\n   108→- Check: `results/full_head_sweep/`\n   109→\n   110→C15. Perplexity matching survives: d=-1.67, p=0.002, n=8 strict pairs\n   111→- Check: `results/perplexity_repairing/`\n   112→\n   113→C16. Multi-seed: all 5 seeds give identical d=-1.751\n   114→- Check: `results/power_up/multi_seed_summary_20260306.json`\n   115→\n   116→C17. FDR: 30/36 survive at alpha=0.05\n   117→- Check: `results/fdr_correction/`\n   118→\n   119→**Circuit & Representation (Claims 18-22)**\n   120→\n   121→C18. L27H10 effective rank: 7.28 → 5.91, d=-1.54\n   122→- Check: `results/svd_circuits/`\n   123→\n   124→C19. L5H29 expansion d=2.93\n   125→- Check: Same as C18\n   126→\n   127→C20. Concept erasure: d=-1.82 before, d=-1.82 after, delta=0.005\n   128→- Check: `results/` for concept erasure files\n   129→\n   130→C21. DII at L27: every PCA dimension shows R_V ≈ 0.41\n   131→- Check: `results/dii_intervention/`\n   132→\n   133→C22. RSA: max dissimilarity at L28 (distance 0.307)\n   134→- Check: `results/rsa/`\n   135→\n   136→**Safety & Scaling (Claims 23-25)**\n   137→\n   138→C23. AUROC = 0.909 for self-referential detection\n   139→- Check: `results/safety/` or `results/classifier_evaluation/`\n   140→\n   141→C24. Genuine vs deceptive: d=-0.06\n   142→- Check: Same as C23\n   143→\n   144→C25. Scaling: R²=0.047 with 8 data points (paper line 472)\n   145→- Check: `results/scaling_law/` or `results/scaling_gap/`\n   146→\n   147→---\n   148→\n   149→## PART B: ORPHAN FINDINGS SCAN\n   150→\n   151→Search these directories for significant findings NOT mentioned in the paper:\n   152→\n   153→1. `docs/findings/` — Read ALL 5 files. List any finding not in the paper.\n   154→2. `RECOVERED_GOLD/` — Read ALL 7 files. List any finding not in the paper.\n   155→3. `docs/findings/NEURIPS_CANDIDATE_2026-02-20.md` — Is the GQA headspace finding in the paper?\n   156→4. `docs/findings/R_V_BEHAVIORAL_DISSOCIATION.md` — Is this dissociation acknowledged in the paper?\n   157→5. `results/phase1_cross_architecture/runs/` — Are there models tested but not reported?\n   158→6. `industry_grade/` — Any findings here that should be in the paper?\n   159→\n   160→For each orphan finding, provide:\n   161→```\n   162→### Orphan [ID]: [description]\n   163→- **Source file:** [path]\n   164→- **Key stat:** [value]\n   165→- **Should be in paper?** YES_CRITICAL / YES_USEFUL / NO_IRRELEVANT\n   166→- **Why:** [brief reason]\n   167→```\n   168→\n   169→---\n   170→\n   171→## PART C: CODE CONSISTENCY CHECK\n   172→\n   173→1. **R_V computation:** Compare the formula in these files:\n   174→   - `src/metrics/rv.py` (canonical)\n   175→   - `geometric_lens/metrics.py` (alternative)\n   176→   - `CANONICAL_CODE/` (any files here)\n   177→   - Paper equation (lines 110-119)\n   178→   - Are they all computing the same thing? If not, which results use which code path?\n   179→\n   180→2. **Layer selection:** Compare layer choices across:\n   181→   - `geometric_lens/models.py` (model registry)\n   182→   - `src/core/` or `src/experiments/`\n   183→   - The paper's stated layers (line 120-121)\n   184→   - CRITICAL: What layers does the registry use for OPT and GPT-2? Are they at ~16% and ~84% depth?\n   185→\n   186→3. **Prompt bank:** \n   187→   - `prompts/bank.json` — how many prompts per category?\n   188→   - Are the same prompts used across all experiments?\n   189→   - Do power_up results use the same bank as mode_atlas results?\n   190→\n   191→---\n   192→\n   193→## PART D: CONTRADICTION MAP\n   194→\n   195→After completing Parts A-C, fill in this summary:\n   196→\n   197→```\n   198→## CONTRADICTION SUMMARY\n   199→\n   200→### Paper claims data CONTRADICTS:"}]},"uuid":"a7a1efa8-89e1-4bf3-9df7-6f20b92ba97e","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:43.517Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"29b4e8d0-4eac-4cbf-96ce-04ac4a66fc29","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
